INSERT INTO comprension_texts (subject_id, level, grades, title, text_content, questions) VALUES
('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'The Lasting Impact of Brexit', 'When the United Kingdom formally left the European Union in January 2020, few could predict the full extent of the changes that would follow. Brexit was presented by its supporters as an opportunity to regain sovereignty, control immigration and negotiate trade deals on Britain''s own terms. Its critics, on the other hand, warned of economic disruption, diplomatic isolation and lasting divisions within British society. Several years later, the consequences have become clearer, although still hotly debated. Trade with the European Union, historically the UK''s largest partner, has become more bureaucratic: exporters face additional paperwork, veterinary checks on food products and delays at the border. Some small companies have even chosen to stop selling to European clients altogether because of the increased costs. The labour market has also shifted, as many workers from continental Europe have returned home, creating shortages in sectors such as hospitality, agriculture and lorry driving. At the same time, supporters of Brexit point to new international agreements and to regulatory flexibility in areas like financial services or artificial intelligence. Politically, the debate over Northern Ireland, which remains closely linked to EU rules to preserve peace on the island, continues to test the patience of all parties involved. Public opinion, once sharply divided, has gradually shifted towards a more nuanced view, with a growing number of Britons wondering whether the relationship with Brussels should evolve. Whether Brexit proves to be a historic turning point or merely a difficult transition, its effects will shape British society for decades.',
'[{"pregunta":"When did the UK formally leave the EU?","opciones":["January 2016","January 2020","June 2016","December 2023"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which sectors face labour shortages after Brexit?","opciones":["Banking and insurance","Hospitality, agriculture and lorry driving","Software and gaming","Aviation and tourism agencies"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Why is Northern Ireland a sensitive issue?","opciones":["It remains linked to EU rules to preserve peace","It has rejected Brexit","It is part of France","It is an independent republic"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"How has public opinion evolved?","opciones":["Towards a more nuanced view","Towards total support","Towards indifference","Towards violent protest"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'Climate Refugees: A Growing Reality', 'Climate change is no longer a distant threat confined to scientific reports; it is actively reshaping where and how millions of people live. Rising sea levels, more frequent hurricanes, prolonged droughts and devastating floods are already forcing entire communities to abandon their homes. The term climate refugee, though not formally recognised in international law, is increasingly used to describe individuals who are displaced by environmental conditions linked to the warming planet. Unlike traditional refugees fleeing war or political persecution, climate migrants often lack clear legal protection, leaving them in a precarious position when they cross national borders. The countries most affected are frequently those that have contributed the least to global emissions. Small island states in the Pacific, low-lying deltas in Bangladesh and arid regions in sub-Saharan Africa face the most immediate pressures. Internal displacement is already massive: the International Organization for Migration estimates that tens of millions of people are forced to move within their own countries each year because of climate-related disasters. International responses remain fragmented. Some nations are investing in adaptation projects such as flood defences, drought-resistant crops or relocation of coastal villages, while others push for new legal frameworks that would grant climate migrants recognised rights. Meanwhile, debates continue about responsibility: who should pay for the losses and damages caused by emissions produced elsewhere? As global temperatures keep rising, addressing climate displacement will require coordinated action in areas from urban planning to humanitarian assistance and diplomacy.',
'[{"pregunta":"Is the term climate refugee formally recognised in international law?","opciones":["Yes, fully","No, not formally","Only in Europe","Only since last year"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which countries face the most immediate pressures?","opciones":["Industrialised economies","Small island states, Bangladesh and parts of Africa","Arctic nations only","Urban megacities only"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"How many people are displaced internally each year due to disasters?","opciones":["A few thousand","Tens of millions","Exactly one million","Less than a hundred"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What kind of debate do climate refugees raise?","opciones":["About responsibility for emissions and losses","About tourist visas","About postal services","About space exploration"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'Quantum Computing Comes of Age', 'For decades, quantum computing seemed like a fascinating theoretical idea more than a practical tool. Today, however, research laboratories and technology giants claim that the field is entering a new phase in which real, useful machines are beginning to emerge. Unlike classical computers, which represent information as bits with a value of zero or one, quantum computers rely on qubits capable of existing in multiple states at the same time thanks to superposition, and of being mysteriously linked through entanglement. These properties allow quantum machines, in principle, to solve certain problems much faster than even the most powerful supercomputers. The potential applications range from designing new drugs and materials to optimising complex logistics, simulating chemical reactions and breaking or improving cryptography. Nevertheless, turning these theoretical advantages into reality is extraordinarily difficult. Qubits are extremely sensitive to noise and temperature, which means they require highly controlled environments, often near absolute zero, and sophisticated error correction techniques. Researchers are currently exploring several physical implementations, including superconducting circuits, trapped ions, photons and neutral atoms, with no clear winner yet. Governments and private companies are investing heavily in the race to reach what experts call useful quantum advantage, the point at which a quantum machine solves a valuable problem better than any classical alternative. Meanwhile, cybersecurity experts are already preparing for the moment when quantum computers could threaten current encryption, designing so-called post-quantum algorithms. Whatever the timeline, quantum computing is likely to transform several industries in the coming decades.',
'[{"pregunta":"What unit does a quantum computer use?","opciones":["A bit","A byte","A qubit","A pixel"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"Which property allows qubits to be mysteriously linked?","opciones":["Superposition","Entanglement","Simulation","Compilation"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Why are qubits difficult to maintain?","opciones":["Because they are too large","Because they are very sensitive to noise and temperature","Because they cost nothing","Because they need sunlight"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What are post-quantum algorithms for?","opciones":["Replacing classical hardware","Resisting future quantum attacks","Generating random numbers only","Teaching children"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'Mental Health Awareness in Modern Society', 'Over the past decade, awareness of mental health has moved from the margins of public debate to become a central topic in education, workplaces and media. Whereas in the past many people suffered in silence because of stigma, prejudice or simple lack of information, today campaigns, celebrities and health professionals encourage open conversations about anxiety, depression, burnout and other psychological conditions. This change has contributed to saving lives, as individuals who recognise their symptoms are more likely to seek support and follow treatment. Nevertheless, improved awareness alone is not enough. Many health systems remain overwhelmed, with long waiting lists, insufficient specialists and significant inequalities in access to care. Young people in particular report increasing levels of stress, which experts link to academic pressure, uncertain labour markets, constant exposure to social media and the emotional weight of global crises. Schools are gradually introducing programmes that teach emotional literacy, coping strategies and ways to ask for help, while some companies implement mental health days, counselling services and training for managers. At the same time, critics warn against oversimplifying the issue: turning mental health into a marketing slogan, encouraging self-diagnosis through social media, or reducing complex conditions to a few catchphrases may cause more harm than good. A balanced approach recognises both the importance of everyday habits, such as sleep, exercise and meaningful relationships, and the need for professional treatment when needed. Protecting mental health, ultimately, is a collective responsibility that involves individuals, families, communities and institutions.',
'[{"pregunta":"What has helped reduce stigma around mental health?","opciones":["Campaigns and open conversations","Silence and prejudice","Higher tuition fees","Tourism trends"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What problems remain in many health systems?","opciones":["Long waiting lists and lack of specialists","Too many therapists","Free universal coverage","Low demand"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Why do young people report more stress?","opciones":["Academic pressure, uncertain job markets and social media","Because they sleep too much","Because of empty schedules","Because of cold weather"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What do critics warn against?","opciones":["Oversimplifying mental health into slogans","Seeking any kind of help","Talking about feelings","Reading books"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'Space Colonisation: Dream or Necessity?', 'Humanity has long dreamed of leaving Earth to establish permanent settlements on other worlds. What was once the territory of science fiction is now discussed seriously by space agencies and private companies that envisage crewed missions to the Moon, Mars and beyond within the coming decades. Supporters of space colonisation argue that expanding beyond our planet could guarantee the survival of the species against catastrophic events such as asteroid impacts, pandemics or environmental collapse. They also claim that exploring other worlds stimulates scientific progress, inspires new generations and leads to technological innovations that benefit everyday life. On the other hand, many experts urge caution. Building self-sufficient colonies on hostile environments like Mars would require solving extremely difficult problems, from growing food and recycling water to protecting settlers against radiation and the psychological effects of isolation. Moreover, the resources needed are enormous, raising ethical questions about whether those funds might be better used to address urgent problems on Earth such as poverty, climate change or inequality. There is also a philosophical debate: should humans export their current way of life to other worlds, or first learn to live more sustainably on their original home? Regardless of one''s position, space exploration is already shaping modern science through robotic missions, telescopes and international collaboration. Whether long-term colonisation proves to be a necessity, a luxury or an illusion, the coming decades will reveal how far humanity is willing to travel and at what cost.',
'[{"pregunta":"What do supporters of colonisation argue?","opciones":["It could ensure the survival of the species","That Earth is unlivable now","That robots should replace humans","That travelling is meaningless"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Which difficulties face settlers on Mars?","opciones":["Food, water, radiation and isolation","Traffic jams","Too many tourists","Excessive humidity"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What ethical question do critics raise?","opciones":["Whether funds should address Earth''s urgent problems","Whether astronauts should wear uniforms","Whether Mars belongs to aliens","Whether we should stop reading"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What is already shaping modern science?","opciones":["Robotic missions, telescopes and collaboration","Horse races","Fashion shows","Classical music only"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'The Gig Economy: Flexibility and Precariousness', 'The gig economy refers to a labour model based on short-term, flexible jobs mediated by digital platforms, ranging from ride-hailing and food delivery to freelance design, translation and programming. For workers, this model promises freedom: they can choose when to work, combine several activities and avoid the rigidity of traditional nine-to-five schedules. For businesses and consumers, it offers immediate access to services and a wide pool of talent at competitive prices. As a result, millions of people around the world now earn part or all of their income through gig platforms. However, enthusiasm about flexibility has been accompanied by growing concerns about precariousness. Many gig workers are classified as self-employed rather than as employees, which often means no minimum wage, no paid holidays, limited access to social protection and unstable income. Algorithms decide who receives tasks and at what price, sometimes without transparency or a genuine possibility of appeal. Labour unions and legal systems are beginning to react: in some countries, courts have ruled that certain gig workers should be considered employees, while in others, specific regulations try to balance flexibility and rights. Consumers, too, play a role: opting for ethical platforms or tipping generously can make a difference. The gig economy is unlikely to disappear, but its future depends on whether societies manage to preserve its positive aspects of flexibility and innovation while ensuring decent conditions, predictable earnings and meaningful protection for the people who make it work every day.',
'[{"pregunta":"How are many gig workers classified?","opciones":["As employees with full rights","As self-employed","As civil servants","As interns"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What decides how tasks are assigned on gig platforms?","opciones":["Random lottery","Algorithms","Government offices","Teachers"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What have courts done in some countries?","opciones":["Ruled some gig workers should be employees","Banned digital platforms","Made all gigs illegal","Forced all workers to quit"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What attracts workers to the gig economy?","opciones":["The promise of flexibility","Low pay","Long hours","Strict schedules"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'Urban Farming and Sustainable Cities', 'As global populations concentrate in urban areas, cities face growing pressure to provide healthy food, reduce emissions and adapt to climate change. Urban farming, the practice of growing fruit and vegetables within or near cities, has emerged as a creative response to these challenges. Rooftop gardens, community allotments, vertical farms in unused warehouses and school vegetable plots are becoming increasingly common across the world. Urban farming offers multiple benefits. It shortens the distance between producers and consumers, reducing the carbon footprint of transportation and ensuring fresher products. It also reconnects urban inhabitants with the origins of their food, an experience that can encourage healthier diets and stronger environmental awareness. Moreover, community gardens become social spaces where neighbours meet, exchange knowledge and build solidarity, especially in disadvantaged areas. Some projects focus on educational goals, teaching children about soil, insects and seasons, while others pursue commercial viability through high-tech indoor farms that use hydroponics, aquaponics and LED lighting to grow crops all year round. Of course, urban farming also faces limitations. Available space is scarce and expensive, potential contamination from traffic and old soils requires careful monitoring, and scaling up often demands significant investment. It cannot fully replace traditional rural agriculture, but it can complement it, strengthen resilience and turn concrete landscapes into greener, more livable environments. Combined with sustainable transport, renewable energy and circular waste management, urban farming is a small but meaningful piece of the puzzle of building cities that are both productive and ecologically responsible.',
'[{"pregunta":"What is urban farming?","opciones":["Growing food within or near cities","Raising cattle on motorways","Fishing in rivers","Importing food from abroad"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Which technology is used in high-tech indoor farms?","opciones":["Hydroponics and LED lighting","Wooden ploughs","Windmills only","Steam engines"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What social benefit is mentioned?","opciones":["Community gardens bring neighbours together","Isolation of individuals","Higher noise pollution","Less interaction"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Can urban farming fully replace rural agriculture?","opciones":["No, but it can complement it","Yes, completely","Only in deserts","Only in winter"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'Diversity in the Workplace', 'Modern companies increasingly recognise that a diverse workforce is not only an ethical aspiration but also a strategic advantage. Diversity in the workplace refers to the inclusion of employees from different backgrounds in terms of gender, age, ethnicity, nationality, sexual orientation, religion, disability and professional experience. When managed well, such diversity can foster creativity, improve decision-making and better reflect the variety of customers a business serves. Numerous studies suggest that companies with diverse teams tend to outperform more homogeneous competitors in innovation and financial results. Nevertheless, diversity without inclusion can be superficial or even counterproductive. It is not enough to hire people from different backgrounds if they are not given real opportunities to participate, lead and influence decisions. Inclusive cultures encourage employees to speak up, challenge ideas and bring their authentic selves to work, while leaders actively address biases in recruitment, promotion and daily interactions. This requires training, clear policies, accountability and a willingness to recognise uncomfortable realities. Progress remains uneven. Women continue to be underrepresented in senior positions and in sectors such as technology or engineering; ethnic minorities often face persistent barriers; and people with disabilities struggle to find accessible workplaces. Some companies publish diversity reports, set voluntary targets or introduce mentoring programmes; others remain sceptical about any formal commitment. Building genuinely diverse and inclusive organisations is a long-term process, but one that reflects broader social values and prepares businesses for a complex, interconnected world where varied perspectives can turn everyday challenges into opportunities.',
'[{"pregunta":"What does diversity in the workplace include?","opciones":["Different backgrounds: gender, age, ethnicity, disability, etc.","Only nationality","Only age","Only gender"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What is needed beyond diversity?","opciones":["Inclusion and real opportunities","Higher salaries only","Strict uniforms","Longer meetings"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Which group is underrepresented in senior tech positions?","opciones":["Women","Men","Retired people","Children"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What do some companies do to promote diversity?","opciones":["Publish diversity reports and mentoring programmes","Hide their data","Forbid discussions","Eliminate HR"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'The Rise of Online Learning', 'Online learning has grown from a marginal option to a mainstream component of education worldwide. Universities offer entire degrees online, schools integrate digital platforms into everyday teaching, and millions of learners access free or paid courses on their own. The pandemic of 2020 accelerated this trend, forcing institutions to experiment quickly and demonstrating that remote learning is technically feasible, although not always pedagogically optimal. The advantages are significant. Online courses allow learners from anywhere in the world to access quality content that would otherwise be out of reach. They offer flexibility, which benefits people who work, care for relatives or live far from campuses. They also enable personalised paths, immediate feedback through digital tools and diverse formats that combine videos, simulations, interactive exercises and collaborative forums. For lifelong learners, the availability of short specialised programmes opens new doors to professional retraining or personal curiosity. Nonetheless, online learning presents real challenges. Motivation and self-discipline become even more important without the structure of a physical classroom. Students without reliable internet connections or suitable devices are at risk of falling behind, deepening digital inequality. Human contact, emotional support and the social experience of education cannot be fully replicated on a screen. Teachers often need extensive training to design engaging digital materials and facilitate online interactions. The future of education is likely to be hybrid, combining the best of face-to-face and digital approaches. Used wisely, technology can enrich learning, but it cannot replace the essential role of qualified educators and supportive communities.',
'[{"pregunta":"What accelerated the rise of online learning?","opciones":["The pandemic of 2020","The invention of radio","The Industrial Revolution","The discovery of electricity"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What is a clear advantage of online learning?","opciones":["Flexibility and global access to content","Obligatory uniforms","Identical timetables for all","Unlimited paper notebooks"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What problem deepens digital inequality?","opciones":["Lack of reliable internet and devices","Too many libraries","Surplus of teachers","Long summer holidays"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What is the likely future of education?","opciones":["A hybrid model","Fully in-person","Fully robotic","Fully silent"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'The Nuclear Energy Debate', 'Nuclear energy has been at the centre of energy debates for decades, and it remains one of the most divisive topics in discussions about how to fight climate change. Supporters argue that nuclear power is a reliable, low-carbon source of electricity that can provide steady output regardless of weather conditions, something that wind and solar energy cannot offer on their own. They stress that modern reactors are safer than older designs, that technologies such as small modular reactors could reduce costs and construction times, and that nuclear power has already helped several countries reduce emissions on a large scale. Opponents, however, point to serious concerns. Accidents such as Chernobyl and Fukushima are often cited as reminders of the potentially catastrophic consequences of mistakes or natural disasters. The long-term management of radioactive waste remains unresolved, with few countries operating permanent deep storage facilities. Building new plants is expensive and frequently affected by delays and cost overruns, making the economic case complicated compared with rapidly falling prices of renewables. There are also concerns about the possible link between civilian nuclear technology and weapons proliferation. Between these two positions, many governments are taking a pragmatic approach: extending the life of existing safe plants while massively investing in renewables and energy efficiency. The role of nuclear energy in the future mix depends not only on technological and economic factors but also on public trust, political decisions and the urgency of reducing greenhouse gas emissions within a limited window of time.',
'[{"pregunta":"What do supporters of nuclear energy highlight?","opciones":["Its reliability and low-carbon output","Its fuel is free","It produces no waste","It needs no cooling"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Which accidents do opponents cite?","opciones":["Chernobyl and Fukushima","Hurricane Katrina","Titanic","Gulf of Mexico oil spill"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What remains unresolved?","opciones":["Long-term management of radioactive waste","The need for oxygen","The colour of reactors","The size of turbines"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What pragmatic approach do governments take?","opciones":["Extending safe plants and investing in renewables","Closing everything","Ignoring climate change","Returning to coal massively"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'Philosophy of Mind and Consciousness', 'The philosophy of mind explores one of the deepest questions in human thought: what is the nature of consciousness and how does it relate to the physical world? For centuries, philosophers have wondered whether the mind is separate from the body, as the French thinker René Descartes famously argued, or whether mental states are ultimately nothing more than physical processes in the brain. Modern science has enormously increased our knowledge of neurons, synapses and neural networks, and yet subjective experience, the feeling of being someone, remains difficult to explain. This puzzle is sometimes called the hard problem of consciousness. Different theories compete to offer an answer. Materialist approaches argue that all mental phenomena can in principle be reduced to physical processes, while dualist theories maintain that the mind has a distinct, non-physical nature. Functionalism proposes that mental states are defined by the roles they play rather than by the material they are made of, which would imply that in theory a sufficiently sophisticated machine could be conscious. Other thinkers adopt panpsychism, the view that some form of experience is a fundamental feature of all matter. Advances in neuroscience, artificial intelligence and cognitive science have reinvigorated these debates. Questions once considered purely theoretical now have practical consequences: how should we treat animals whose consciousness we only partly understand, and what would we owe to a machine that claimed to feel? Whatever position one adopts, the philosophy of mind reminds us that behind apparently simple everyday experience lies one of the most profound mysteries science and philosophy have ever faced.',
'[{"pregunta":"Who famously argued mind and body are separate?","opciones":["Descartes","Aristotle","Socrates","Einstein"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What is the hard problem of consciousness?","opciones":["Explaining subjective experience","Building bigger brains","Measuring neurons","Curing colds"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What does functionalism propose?","opciones":["Mental states are defined by their roles","Minds are made of metal","Consciousness is impossible","Only humans think"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Why do these debates now have practical consequences?","opciones":["Because of animals and possible conscious machines","Because of fashion trends","Because of sports events","Because of tourism"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{2}', 'Ethical Consumerism in Daily Life', 'Ethical consumerism is the idea that, through everyday purchases, people can express moral values and influence the behaviour of producers, retailers and governments. Supporters argue that in a globalised economy, consumers have real power: choosing fair-trade coffee, organic cotton, cruelty-free cosmetics or locally produced food sends signals that gradually reshape entire supply chains. Over recent decades, ethical labels and certifications have multiplied, helping consumers to identify products that meet specific standards concerning labour conditions, environmental protection, animal welfare or carbon emissions. However, the practice of ethical consumerism raises complex questions. First, information is often incomplete: a product may appear ethical in one aspect, such as recyclable packaging, while causing problems in another, like excessive water use. Consumers rarely have time to investigate every detail, and misleading advertising, sometimes called greenwashing, can exploit good intentions. Second, ethical options are frequently more expensive, which means that only people with comfortable incomes can fully engage with them. This creates inequalities between those who can afford to align their purchases with their values and those who simply cannot. Third, some critics argue that focusing excessively on individual choices distracts from structural changes: real progress requires regulation, collective action and transformation of business models, not only adjustments to personal shopping carts. Despite these limitations, ethical consumerism can contribute to a broader shift, especially when combined with civic engagement, political participation and pressure on companies. Informed, critical and organised consumers can, little by little, encourage markets to move in a more sustainable and fair direction.',
'[{"pregunta":"What is ethical consumerism?","opciones":["Expressing moral values through purchases","Buying only imported goods","Refusing all products","Saving all income"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What is greenwashing?","opciones":["Misleading advertising exploiting good intentions","Cleaning rivers","Painting walls green","Recycling plastics"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What inequality does the text mention?","opciones":["Ethical products are often more expensive","Everyone earns the same","No one has savings","Products are always cheap"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What do some critics argue?","opciones":["That structural changes are also needed","That consumers have no power","That labels are enough","That ethics are irrelevant"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb);



